mjr@tis.com (Marcus J. Ranum) writes:
[...]
>	Another approach is to use a cryptographic calculator like
>the Digital Pathways SNK or Racal Watchword. When you try to log in,
>you get a challenge number, which you key into your calculator, which
>performs some mystical maneuvers based on a PIN you type into it, and
>returns a response. I.e:
>
>>otter-> telnet otter
>>Trying 192.33.112.117 ...
>>Connected to otter.
>>Escape character is '^]'.
>>
>>
>>SunOS UNIX (otter)
>>
>>login: mjr
>>SNK Challenge: 80313
>>Response: 3918493
>>
>>Last login: Tue Oct 19 08:05:52 on console
>>SunOS Release 4.1.3 (OTTER) #3: Mon Jun 21 15:07:30 EDT 1993
>>...
>
>	In this case, there's a shared secret between the server and
>the cryptographic calculator, which typically DES-encrypts the challenge
>and compares it with what the user returns. The advantage is that the
>shared secret is concealed from the user, and you need the device to
>use the system.

Wouldn't this method be open to a known plain text attack?

